U.S. Election Prediction Modeling

Zach Jordan

Abstract

In the past few U.S. elections, the polling of presidential candidates has been wildly off and a poor predictor of actual results. This analysis seeks to find an alternative solution to current polling standards by looking at data from the entirety of the term leading up to the election. We set a hypothesis that elections are a predictable process and that Americans vote not based upon the candidate, but rather what the current political party does in office. We will investigate this through a series of logistic regression functions, measuring the impact that each variable has on the determination of the next president’s political affiliation. Although the results were inconclusive, it creates reason for this study to be investigated further and more in-depth.

Introduction

This data set is comprised of data from “The American Presidency Project” and includes a variety of statistics from the previous 12 U.S. presidential terms (1972 - 2016). I did not go back any further in the election process because previous elections had a relevant impact of a third-party candidate and this analysis focuses on the two major parties in the United States, Democratic and Republican. Within this data set we also have 3 impeachment proceedings, which do not occur often outside the 40 year time span. To begin we will first load in our data and format it to better suit our needs.

EDA

Now that we have our data loaded in properly, we can begin our exploratory data analysis and see what exactly we’re working with.

Single Variable Graphs

Voter Turnout

From this graph we are able to see the total number of voters in the election prior to each year. The number is increasing as time goes on, which could mean either the population of voters is increasing or the political activism is becoming stronger. We also see a spike from the 1992 election, which could be due to a strong candidate or because the U.S. doesn’t like the current president/presidential party.

voter_turnout <- elections %>%
    filter(State == "Alabama") %>%
    ggplot(aes(Year, Previous_Voter_Turnout))+
    geom_bar(stat = "identity", color = "black") +
    theme_bw() +
    labs(x="Next Election Year", y="Number of Voters (millions)", title="Voter Turnout Prior to Each Election") +
    theme(
        plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5, face = "bold", size = 15),
        axis.title = element_text(size = 11),
        )

voter_turnout

Electoral Split

This shows the difference in electoral votes between the two parties in an election year. We see that the two parties are slowly getting closer together, which could be a reason why the polling is so off.

electoral_votes <- elections %>%
    filter(Year != "2020") %>%
    group_by(Year, Winner) %>% 
    summarise(Total_Electors = sum(Total_Electors)) %>%
    ungroup() %>%
    ggplot(aes(x=Year, y=Total_Electors, fill=Winner)) +
    geom_bar(stat='identity', position='dodge', color ="black") +
    scale_fill_manual(values = c("blue", "red"))  +
    theme_bw() +
    labs(x="Election Year", y="Electoral Votes", title="Spread of Electoral Votes by Party", fill = "Party") +
    theme(
        plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5, face = "bold", size = 15),
        axis.title = element_text(size = 11),
        )

States Matching Winning Party

Logistic Regression Modeling

Now that we have a grasp of the data set, we’ll begin our logistic regression modeling.

State by State

To start, we’ll do a prediction model of a single state, which gives us a formula we can use for other states. From the data below we see that adding all these variables doesn’t offer a good prediction. The reason for this, is that our data is too wide for how many entries we have. For a quality multivariate logistic regression, we would want more like 30 different elections, but we only have the 12, hence why none of the variables are statistically relevant. Instead we can try and do one of the entire country since it offers more than 12 rows.

Alabama <- elections %>%
    filter(State == "Alabama")


predict_Alabama <- glm(as.factor(Winner) ~ Current_President_Party + President_Initial_Approval + President_Initial_Disapproval + President_Mid_Approval + President_Mid_Disapproval + President_News_Conference + President_Ex_Orders + President_Last_Approval + President_Last_Disapproval + President_Party_Mid_Change_House + President_Party_Mid_Change_Senate, Alabama, family = "binomial")
summary(predict_Alabama)

Countrywide

With the data we have below we realize another crucial feature of our data. This data was originally created with the purpose of doing several smaller logistic regressions of the states and then adding them with their respective electoral votes to get an overall national winner. That however is not possible as prove by the previous state by state attempt. Because of this fact, the data only has 12 unique rows, one for every election year, and so the data is the exact same as the state by state comparison. In order to fix this, we would need to collect more election data for many years prior. There is, however, a way we can use this data and find the statistical relevance of a single variable.

elections_ <- elections %>%
    filter(Year != "2020") %>%
    filter(State == "Alabama")

keep <- function (x) {
    if (is.factor(x) || is.character(x)) {
        length(unique(x[!is.na(x)])) > 1
    } else TRUE
}

elections_keep <- elections_[sapply(elections_, keep)] 

predict_Alabama <- glm(as.factor(National_Winner) ~ . -Winner -Year -Total_Electors, elections_keep, family = "binomial")
summary(predict_Alabama)

Logistic Regression Modeling: Revised

Here we can load in a new data set that ignores the state variable and instead gives priority to the year. While we many not be able to do a multivariate logistic regression, we can look into individual variables and determine if there exists and correlation to predicting the election. I have listed the top three variables when it comes to predicting the U.S. election.

elections_total <- read.csv("/Users/z_jordan/Desktop/Last Chance.csv", na.strings=c(""))

elections_total$Year <- factor(elections_total$Year)
elections_total$Previous_Voter_Turnout <- parse_number(as.character(elections_total$Previous_Voter_Turnout))
elections_total$Current_President_Party <- factor(elections_total$Current_President_Party)
elections_total$Change_In_Power <- factor(elections_total$Change_In_Power)
elections_total$Impeachment_Presence <- factor(elections_total$Impeachment_Presence)
elections_total$National_Winner <- factor(elections_total$National_Winner)

Top Three Predictor Varibles

One

For the first variable we are attempting to predict the president elect’s party based solely upon the number of seats the president’s party lost or gained during the midterm. We create the model and then at the bottom we calculate the R-squared value and the a p-value for it. Surprisingly, this piece of data has a potentially large correlation (R-squared of 0.428) with the party determination, and it is statistically significant (p-value of 0.00826). With more data we might be able to add another variable to strengthen this model.

predict_election <- glm(as.factor(National_Winner) ~ President_Party_Mid_Change_House, elections_total, family = "binomial")
summary(predict_election)

It is close enough to being statistically relevant that it deserves more exploration.

Logistic Regression Modeling: Ablation

For our final portion of modeling, we attempt to answer what if questions about the data. For this I chose to explore the 2016 election results. They were very close in terms of the popular vote and the elector vote didn’t match the popular vote. Clearly, it was a close electoral race, and for that reason we will load in the last data set, with the only difference being the 2016 party that won. All the other data will stay the same, but the party that won and the current president’s political affiliation will be changed from ‘Republican’ to ‘Democrat’

elections_total_ablation <- read.csv("/Users/z_jordan/Desktop/What_IF.csv", na.strings=c(""))

elections_total_ablation$Year <- factor(elections_total_ablation$Year)
elections_total_ablation$Previous_Voter_Turnout <- parse_number(as.character(elections_total_ablation$Previous_Voter_Turnout))
elections_total_ablation$Current_President_Party <- factor(elections_total_ablation$Current_President_Party)
elections_total_ablation$Change_In_Power <- factor(elections_total_ablation$Change_In_Power)
elections_total_ablation$Impeachment_Presence <- factor(elections_total_ablation$Impeachment_Presence)
elections_total_ablation$National_Winner <- factor(elections_total_ablation$National_Winner)

Ablation of Predictor Varibles

For this, we’ll explore the exact same variables as before as look at the differences in the results.

One

We see that with the Democratic win, the correlation drops a bit, but it still remains statistically important. The relatively close R-squared could be due to the fact that it was a close election and the fact that it is lesser could mean that the model predicted ‘Republican’ for this model. Either way it is an interesting statistic and should be explored further.

Potential Changes

There are a couple of changes I would make to the data set before I continued exploring its prediction capabilities. First, and most important, it needs more data points to actual be useful as a predictor. While it shows potential, a coin flip would be just as accurate as the models created. Second, I would gather more data from the year, just to see if there was an odd variable that better predicted elections, such as stock market trading.

Conclusion

Overall, the results found were inconclusive because while it didn’t predict the elections very well, it showed possibility in some of the variables. If more data was collected and added to the set we might be able to find conclusive results, but as of right now there exists a reasonable suspicion that these variables could predict which party will win the election. This concludes my analysis and I leave any results up to interpretation.
